  "doc_id": "22858",
  "text": "Lindell et al. [CITATION_1] analyzed the Mayo CT screening trial and assessed the VDT of 48 lung cancers. The VDT for bronchoalveolar cell carcinomas (780 Ϯ 1,545 days) and adenocarcinoma (746 Ϯ 1,238 days) was substantially longer than the VDT for squamous cell cancer (103 Ϯ 58), non-small cell lung cancer, not otherwise specified (81 Ϯ 31), and small cell cancer (49 Ϯ 36). Thirteen lung cancers (27%) had VDTs Ͼ400 days. Eleven of the 13 lung cancers with VDTs Ͼ400 days were in women. While the existence of \"overdiagnosed\" lung cancer is questioned by some, many physicians believe that it is a significant problem in the interpretation of current nonrandomized screening studies. The frequency of overdiagnosis is uncertain, but the reports summarized above suggest that perhaps 25% of CT-detected cancers may be \"overdiagnosis.\"",
